		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						Autotechnia, et Idiopraxia semper singularis.
						Nunq[uam] Sua[e] immemor vnica[e]
						perfectionis. Seipsam Singulis momentis cogans )
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						aliquid addere excellentius.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Qua[e]uis animi, corporis, fortuna[e] facultas, omni
						specioso,
						secretoq[ue] incremento exertissimè multiplicanda.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Incredibilem addit dictis, factisq[ue] vim perpetuus vigor,
						magis magisq[ue] multiplicatus.
						Exagerat singulas
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						partes
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Totus arte, et
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Virtute cumulatus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Self-discipline and individual praxis are always singular.
				Never forget your own unique perfection, and always consider
				adding something even more excellent to singular moments.
				Any ability of the mind, body, or fortune must be stretched out and 
				multiplied in all degrees both apparent and hidden.
				A continuous vigor adds incredible force to both words and deeds,
				a vigor which is more and more increased.
				Entirely in art and brought together in virtue, such vigor magnifies
				all the singular parts.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Carmen Hermolai Barbari.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Ermolao Barbaro"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The song of Ermolao Barbaro.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Exertissimo animi, corporisq[ue] incremento Singula |
						efferenda.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Singular matters must be carried out by the widest degree in both mind and body. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Suas etiam tacendi vices discretè obseruat Eutrapelus: sed cum rogatur, aut pra[e]gnans
						offertur opportunitas; effundit sapientia[e], eloquentia[e]q[ue] fluentissimas fontes.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Eutrapelus discreetly observes his own vices in silence, but when questioned, or when a pregnant opportunity arises,
				he overflows the most flowing founts of wisdom and eloquence.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
